insert into public.questions
  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1857, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Coupon Collector Die$x$, 'standard', 3, 'intern', 'Global', $x$You roll a fair six-sided die repeatedly. On average, how many rolls does it take until you have seen every one of the six faces at least once?$x$, $x$["Coupon Collector Problem", "Sum Of Geometric Waiting Times", "After k Distinct Faces P(new)=(6-k)/6", "Expected Wait=6/(6-k)", "Total=6(1+1/2+1/3+1/4+1/5+1/6)", "Answer About 14.7 Rolls", "Last Face Alone Takes 6"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I treat this as the coupon collector problem. Think of it in stages: the wait to see the first brand-new face, then the next, and so on. When I already have k distinct faces, the chance any given roll shows a new face is (6 minus k) over 6, so the expected number of rolls to get that new face is 6 over (6 minus k), because it is a geometric waiting time. I sum those expectations across the six stages. That gives 6 over 6, plus 6 over 5, plus 6 over 4, down to 6 over 1. Factoring out the 6, that is 6 times the harmonic sum 1 plus one-half plus one-third plus one-quarter plus one-fifth plus one-sixth. The bracket is about 2.45, so the answer is roughly 14.7 rolls. The intuition that surprises people is that the very last face, on its own, takes 6 rolls on average, since by then each roll is a new face only one time in six.$x$),
(1858, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Ant On A Cube$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$An ant sits at one corner of a cube and at each step walks along an edge to one of the three neighbouring corners, each equally likely. What is the expected number of steps for it to reach the corner diagonally opposite its start?$x$, $x$["Random Walk On Cube Graph", "Group Vertices By Distance 0/1/2/3", "Set Up Expected-Value Equations By State", "E0=1+E1, E1=1+(1/3)E0+(2/3)E2, E2=1+(2/3)E1", "Solve Linear System Gives E0=10", "Symmetry Reduces Eight Vertices To Four States"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I exploit symmetry and group the eight corners by how many edges they are from the start: distance 0 is the start, distance 1 the three neighbours, distance 2 the next three, and distance 3 the target. Let E0, E1, E2 be the expected steps to the target from each layer. From the start every move goes to a distance-1 corner, so E0 equals 1 plus E1. From a distance-1 corner, one of its three edges goes back to the start and two go to distance-2 corners, so E1 equals 1 plus one-third E0 plus two-thirds E2. From a distance-2 corner, two edges go back to distance 1 and one reaches the target, so E2 equals 1 plus two-thirds E1. Solving the system, substituting down gives two-ninths of E0 equal to twenty over nine, so E0 is 10. So it takes 10 steps on average. A neat sanity check is the middle states, E1 equals 9 and E2 equals 7, which sit close together, fitting how well connected the cube is.$x$),
(1859, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Full House Probability$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$From a standard 52-card deck, five cards are dealt at random. What is the probability of being dealt a full house, that is three of one rank and two of another?$x$, $x$["Total Hands C(52,5)=2,598,960", "Choose Rank For Trips 13 Then C(4,3)", "Choose Different Rank For Pair 12 Then C(4,2)", "Trips And Pair Are Distinct Roles So No Symmetry Divide", "Count=13*4*12*6=3,744", "Probability About 0.14 Percent", "Roughly 1 In 694"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I count favourable hands over total hands. The total number of five-card hands is 52 choose 5, which is 2,598,960. For a full house I build the hand in steps. First pick the rank that supplies the three of a kind, 13 ways, then choose which three of its four suits, 4 choose 3 which is 4. Then pick a different rank for the pair, 12 ways, and choose two of its four suits, 4 choose 2 which is 6. The key subtlety is that the trips rank and the pair rank play different roles, so I do not divide by any symmetry factor; multiplying gives 13 times 4 times 12 times 6, which is 3,744 hands. Dividing by 2,598,960 gives about 0.00144, so roughly one-seventh of one percent, or about one hand in 694. The thing to get right in interviews is not double counting or over-symmetrising the two ranks, since three of a kind and a pair are genuinely distinct roles.$x$),
(1860, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Secretary Problem$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$You interview 100 candidates one at a time in random order and must hire or reject each on the spot, with no recalls. You only care about hiring the single best candidate. What strategy maximises your chance, and roughly what probability of success does it give?$x$, $x$["Optimal Stopping / Secretary Problem", "Reject First Fraction As Calibration Sample", "Then Hire First Candidate Better Than All Seen", "Optimal Cutoff Is About n/e", "Reject First ~37 Then Take Next Record", "Success Probability About 1/e Or 37 Percent", "Threshold And Success Both Converge To 1/e"]$x$::jsonb, $x$This is the classic secretary or optimal-stopping problem. The right approach is a look-then-leap rule: reject the first chunk of candidates no matter how good they are, just to calibrate, then hire the first later candidate who is better than everyone seen so far. The question is how big to make that calibration sample. The answer, for large numbers, is to reject the first fraction one over e of the pool, which is about 37 percent, so here roughly the first 37 candidates. After that, I take the next person who beats all the earlier ones. The beautiful result is that the probability of actually landing the single best candidate also converges to one over e, about 37 percent, surprisingly high given you are committing blind. The intuition is a trade-off: a longer calibration window sets a higher bar but risks the best person being in the rejected block; one over e balances those two failure modes. I would quote the cutoff and the success rate as both being about 37 percent.$x$),
(1861, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Doubling Coin Game$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A pot starts at 2 dollars. I flip a fair coin; on heads the pot doubles and I flip again, on the first tails the game ends and you win whatever is in the pot. What is the fair value of this game, and how does that change if the casino can pay out at most about one million dollars?$x$, $x$["St Petersburg Paradox", "Ends On First Tails, Pot 2^k With Probability 1/2^k", "Each Term Contributes One Dollar To EV", "Uncapped Expected Value Diverges To Infinity", "Cap At 2^20 ~ 1,048,576", "Capped Fair Value Only About 21 Dollars", "Tail Probabilities Tiny So Cap Bites Hard"]$x$::jsonb, $x$This is the St Petersburg paradox. If the game ends on the first tails after k flips, the pot is 2 to the power k, and the probability of reaching exactly that point is one over 2 to the power k. So the expected payoff from each possible stopping point is 2 to the k times one over 2 to the k, which is exactly one dollar, every single time. Summing over all k, one plus one plus one forever, the expected value diverges to infinity. So in theory the fair price is unbounded, yet nobody would pay even fifty dollars, which is the paradox. The resolution in practice is the payout cap. If the casino can pay at most about one million, that is two to the twentieth, then every branch beyond twenty flips is capped, and those terms stop contributing a fresh dollar each. Summing the capped series, the fair value collapses to only about 21 dollars. The lesson is that the infinite expectation lives entirely in astronomically rare, astronomically large payoffs, so any real-world cap brings it down to a very ordinary number.$x$),
(1862, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$First Ace In Deck$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A standard 52-card deck is shuffled and you turn cards over one at a time from the top. On average, what is the position of the first ace, that is the expected number of cards you turn over up to and including the first ace you see?$x$, $x$["Symmetry Or Spacing Argument, Not Brute Summation", "Four Aces Split 48 Non-Aces Into Five Gaps", "Each Gap Has Equal Expected Size 48/5=9.6", "Cards Before First Ace Equals The Leading Gap", "Expected Position=9.6+1=10.6", "General Rule (n+1)/(k+1) Gives 53/5"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The trick is symmetry, not brute force. The deck has four aces and forty-eight non-aces. Imagine laying the forty-eight non-aces in a row first; the four aces then drop into the gaps around them. There are five such gaps: before the first non-ace, between each pair, and after the last. By symmetry every gap holds the same expected number of non-aces, so each gap averages forty-eight over five, which is 9.6 cards. The number of cards I turn over before hitting the first ace is just the count sitting in that opening gap, so on average I see 9.6 non-aces and then the ace itself. That makes the expected position of the first ace 9.6 plus 1, which is 10.6, or 53 over 5. The clean general rule is that for k items shuffled into n others, the expected position of the first one is (n plus 1) over (k plus 1); here that is 53 over 5. Interviewers like that this avoids any messy summation.$x$),
(1863, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Three Switches One Bulb$x$, 'standard', 3, 'intern', 'Global', $x$There are three on-off light switches outside a windowless room, and exactly one of them controls a single incandescent bulb inside. The door is closed. You may flip the switches as much as you like, but you can only open the door and enter the room once. How do you determine which switch controls the bulb?$x$, $x$["Use Heat As A Second Signal", "Switch One On For Several Minutes", "Turn Switch One Off Then Switch Two On", "Enter Room Once", "Bulb Lit Means Switch Two", "Off And Warm Means Switch One", "Off And Cold Means Switch Three"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The trick is that an incandescent bulb gives me two signals, light and heat, so I effectively get more than one bit of information from a single visit. Here is my plan. I turn switch one on and leave it on for, say, ten minutes so the bulb heats up. Then I turn switch one off and immediately flip switch two on, leaving switch three untouched. Now I open the door and enter just once. If the bulb is lit, it must be switch two, since that is the only one currently on. If the bulb is off but warm to the touch, it is switch one, because it was on long enough to heat the filament before I cut it. If the bulb is off and cold, it has never been powered, so it must be switch three. The insight worth flagging is that I am exploiting a physical property, residual heat, to encode a third state. If the bulb were an LED that stays cool, this elegant solution breaks and I would need a different approach.$x$),
(1864, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Two Hourglasses Timing$x$, 'standard', 3, 'intern', 'Global', $x$You have two hourglasses, one that runs for exactly 7 minutes and one that runs for exactly 11 minutes. You need to boil an egg for precisely 15 minutes. Using only these two hourglasses, how do you measure out 15 minutes, and how quickly can you start the egg?$x$, $x$["Start Both Hourglasses And Egg Together", "Egg Starts Immediately At Time Zero", "Flip Seven When It Empties At Minute Seven", "Eleven Has Four Minutes Left", "Flip Seven Again When Eleven Empties", "Accumulated Sand Drains Final Four Minutes", "Eleven Plus Four Equals Fifteen"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I can start the egg right away at time zero, which is the elegant part. I flip both the 7-minute and 11-minute glasses the moment I drop the egg in. When the 7 runs out at minute seven, the 11 still has four minutes of sand left, so I immediately flip the 7. When the 11 runs out at minute eleven, the 7 has been running again for four minutes, so it now holds four minutes of sand in the bottom and three minutes still up top. At that instant I flip the 7 once more. Those four minutes that had collected in the bottom now drain back down, and when the 7 finally empties, the elapsed time is eleven plus four, exactly fifteen minutes. So the sequence is start both glasses with the egg, flip the 7 at minute seven, flip the 7 again at minute eleven, and pull the egg at minute fifteen. The key realization is that the sand already accumulated in a partly run glass measures a usable interval the instant you invert it, which lets me capture the leftover four minutes.$x$),
(1865, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Bridge And Torch$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Four people must cross a rickety bridge at night. They have one flashlight, the bridge holds at most two people at a time, and anyone crossing must carry the flashlight. Their individual crossing times are 1, 2, 5, and 10 minutes; a pair moves at the slower person's pace. What is the minimum total time for all four to get across, and what is the non-obvious step?$x$, $x$["Answer Is Seventeen Minutes", "One And Two Cross First Two Minutes", "One Returns One Minute", "Five And Ten Cross Together Ten Minutes", "Two Returns Then One And Two Recross", "Pair The Two Slowest Together", "Beats Naive Fast-Shuttle Of Nineteen"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The minimum is seventeen minutes, and the non-obvious idea is that you should send the two slowest people across together so their times overlap rather than stack. The naive approach is to use the fastest person, the one-minute walker, as a permanent shuttle, but that gives nineteen minutes and is suboptimal. Here is the optimal sequence. First, the 1 and 2 cross together, taking two minutes. The 1 returns with the flashlight, one minute, total three. Now the 5 and 10 cross together, which costs ten minutes since the pair moves at the slower pace, total thirteen. The 2, who is already waiting on the far side, returns with the flashlight, two minutes, total fifteen. Finally the 1 and 2 cross together for the last time, two minutes, total seventeen. The whole point is that the expensive ten-minute crossing happens only once and is shared with the five-minute person, instead of the ten ever crossing alone. That insight is what beats the nineteen-minute trap.$x$),
(1866, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Pirate Coin Division$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Five pirates ranked by seniority must split 100 gold coins. The most senior proposes a division; all pirates including the proposer vote, and if at least half approve, it passes. Otherwise the proposer is thrown overboard and the next most senior proposes, repeating. Pirates are perfectly rational, want to maximize gold, and prefer throwing others overboard when indifferent. What does the top pirate propose?$x$, $x$["Solve By Backward Induction", "Two Pirates Proposer Takes All Hundred", "Three Pirates Bribe The Most Junior With One", "Four Pirates Bribe Third-Ranked With One", "Five Pirates Senior Takes Ninety-Eight", "One Coin Each To Pirates Three And Five", "Ties Pass So Senior Needs Own Vote Plus Two"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I solve this by backward induction, labeling the pirates one through five with one the most senior, and working up from the smallest case. If only two are left, four and five, pirate four votes for his own plan; that is fifty percent, which counts as at least half, so it passes and he takes all 100. With three pirates, three needs one extra vote. Five gets nothing in the two-pirate endgame, so three buys five with a single coin and keeps 99. With four pirates, four needs one ally beyond himself. Three would get nothing in the three-pirate outcome, so four hands three one coin and keeps 99. Now all five. Pirate one needs two votes besides his own, three in total. He looks at who ends up with zero if he dies and the four-pirate game runs: that is pirates three and five. So he gives one coin each to three and five, who accept because one beats zero, and he keeps 98. The proposal is 98, 0, 1, 0, 1 from senior to junior.$x$),
(1867, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Prisoners And Switch$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$One hundred prisoners are taken one at a time, in random order with repetition, into a room containing a single light switch. At any point any prisoner may declare that all 100 have visited the room; if correct, all go free, if wrong, all are executed. They may strategize once beforehand but never communicate again. The switch starts in a known position. What strategy guarantees freedom?$x$, $x$["Designate One Counter Prisoner", "Counter Counts Switch Flips", "Ordinary Prisoners Turn Switch On Once Each", "Counter Turns Switch Off And Increments", "Counter Declares At Ninety-Nine", "Requires Known Starting Position Off", "Guarantees Correctness Not Speed"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The team designates one person as the counter; the other ninety-nine are ordinary prisoners, and the switch is a signaling channel. We are told it starts off. Each ordinary prisoner follows one rule: the first time they ever enter and find the switch off, they turn it on, and after that they never touch the switch again. The counter is the only one who turns it back off, and every time he walks in and finds it on, he switches it off and adds one to his private tally. Since each of the ninety-nine ordinary prisoners turns it on exactly once over the whole process, the counter eventually records ninety-nine separate on-events. The moment his tally reaches ninety-nine, he knows for certain that all ninety-nine others, plus himself, have been in the room at least once, so he safely declares that everyone has visited. The known starting position is essential: if it had secretly started on, the count could be off by one and doom them. This guarantees correctness, though it can take a very long time.$x$),
(1868, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Fox Goose Grain Crossing$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A farmer must ferry a fox, a goose, and a sack of grain across a river. His boat holds only himself and one item. If left together unattended, the fox eats the goose, and the goose eats the grain. The fox and grain are safe together. What sequence of crossings gets all three across intact, and what is the key move?$x$, $x$["Take Goose Over First", "Return Empty Then Take Fox Or Grain", "Bring Goose Back On Return Trip", "Drop Goose Take Remaining Item Over", "Finally Return For Goose", "Goose Is The Conflicted Middle Item", "Key Insight Is Shuttling Goose Back"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The goose is the dangerous middle item since it both eats and gets eaten, so every solution revolves around keeping the goose apart from the others, and the key non-obvious move is bringing the goose back across rather than leaving it. Here is the sequence. First I take the goose over and leave it on the far bank, then row back empty. Next I take the fox across, but I cannot leave the fox and goose together, so on my return trip I bring the goose back with me. I drop the goose on the near bank and take the grain across, leaving the fox and grain together on the far side, which is safe. I row back empty one last time and finally carry the goose over. Now all three are across and nothing was ever left in a lethal pairing. That is seven crossings in total. The whole puzzle hinges on realizing the boat can carry items backward; once you accept temporarily undoing progress by re-crossing the goose, the dependencies untangle cleanly.$x$),
(1869, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Rule Of 72$x$, 'core', 3, 'intern', 'Global', $x$An investment compounds at 9 percent a year. Using a mental shortcut, roughly how long does it take to double, and what is the rule you are using?$x$, $x$["Rule of 72 divides 72 by the rate", "72 / 9 = 8 years", "Approximation for compound doubling time", "Works best mid single-digit to low-teens rates", "Cross-check: 1.09^8 is about 1.99x", "Used for quick returns and inflation intuition"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would use the rule of 72, which says doubling time in years is roughly 72 divided by the annual percentage growth rate. At 9 percent, that is 72 over 9, which is exactly 8 years. The logic is that compounding is exponential, and 72 happens to be a clean numerator that approximates the natural-log math very well across the rates bankers care about, say 4 to 15 percent, while also dividing evenly by lots of numbers. If I sanity-check it, 1.09 to the 8th power is about 1.99, so the estimate is essentially spot on. The same trick runs in reverse and across contexts. If inflation is running near 6 percent, prices double in about 12 years, and if a private company is growing revenue at 24 percent, it doubles in roughly 3 years. The cousin is the rule of 70, which is a touch more accurate at low rates, and some people use 69.3, the exact log of 2 times 100, but 72 is the one I would reach for under pressure because the arithmetic is cleaner.$x$),
(1870, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Gauss Series Sum$x$, 'standard', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$Sum every integer from 1 to 100 in your head, then tell me how the same trick gives the sum from 1 to 200.$x$, $x$["Pair first and last into constant sums", "50 pairs of 101 equals 5050", "Formula n times (n+1) over 2", "Gauss pairing insight", "1 to 200 is 200 times 201 / 2 = 20100", "Generalizes to any arithmetic series"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The classic Gauss trick is to pair the numbers from the outside in. One plus 100 is 101, two plus 99 is 101, and so on, and there are 50 such pairs, so the total is 50 times 101, which is 5050. More formally that is n times n plus 1, all over 2, with n equal to 100, giving 100 times 101 over 2, the same 5050. For 1 to 200 I just plug in n equals 200, so it is 200 times 201 over 2. Half of 200 is 100, and 100 times 201 is 20100. Notice it is not simply double the first answer, because both the count of terms and the size of the largest term grew. The pairing idea generalizes to any evenly spaced run. The sum of an arithmetic series is just the number of terms times the average of the first and last term, so summing 1 to 200 is 200 terms times an average of 100.5, which again lands on 20100. That average-of-the-ends framing is the one I find fastest in an interview.$x$),
(1871, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Powers Of Two$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A rumor doubles the number of people who have heard it every day, starting from one person on day zero. After how many days does it exceed one million, and what is 2 to the 20th power?$x$, $x$["2^10 = 1024, roughly one thousand", "2^20 = 1024 squared, about 1.05 million", "Exceeds 1,000,000 on day 20", "Doubling means powers of two", "2^20 = 1,048,576 exact", "Anchor 2^10 ~ 1000 for quick scaling"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Doubling from one person means after d days the count is 2 to the d. The key anchor every banker should memorize is that 2 to the 10th is 1024, just over a thousand. So 2 to the 20th is 1024 squared, and since 1024 is about 1000, that is roughly a million, a little over. Precisely, 1024 times 1024 is 1,048,576, so 2 to the 20th is about 1.05 million. That means on day 20 the rumor first exceeds one million people, because day 19 is only about 524 thousand. The takeaway I would give is that each block of 10 doublings multiplies by roughly a thousand, so 2 to the 30th is about a billion and 2 to the 40th about a trillion. That rule of thumb is incredibly handy for sizing anything exponential, from viral user growth to storage to the chessboard-and-rice puzzle, without ever multiplying two by itself twenty times. I would just remember ten doublings is a kilo, twenty is a mega.$x$),
(1872, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Bond Price Yield$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A bond with a modified duration of 6 yields 4 percent and trades at par. If its yield jumps to 5 percent, estimate the new price in your head, and tell me which way you are erring.$x$, $x$["Price change approx minus duration times yield change", "6 times 1 percent equals a 6 percent drop", "New price roughly 94 per 100 par", "Inverse price-yield relationship", "Linear estimate ignores positive convexity", "Convexity means actual price slightly above 94"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The first-order rule is that the percentage change in a bond price is approximately minus modified duration times the change in yield. Here duration is 6 and yield rises by 1 percentage point, or 0.01, so the price falls by roughly 6 times 1 percent, which is 6 percent. Since it started at par, call it 100, the estimate is about 94. The minus sign matters because price and yield move inversely, so a higher yield means a lower price. The direction of my error is the interesting part. Duration is a straight-line approximation to a curve that is actually convex, bowed toward the origin, so for any real move the true price sits slightly above the line. That positive convexity means I am understating the price, and the real number is a touch above 94, maybe 94 and a small fraction. For a 1 percent move the convexity correction is tiny, but for a large yield swing it matters more, and it is why convexity is friendly to a long bondholder, cushioning losses and amplifying gains.$x$),
(1873, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Smartphones Sold Globally$x$, 'core', 3, 'intern', 'Global', $x$Estimate how many smartphones are sold worldwide in a year. Walk me through your assumptions.$x$, $x$["World population framed near 8 billion", "Smartphone owners estimated, roughly half to 4-4.5bn users", "Replacement cycle assumed around 3-4 years", "Annual sales = installed base divided by replacement cycle", "First-time buyers in growth markets added but base is flattening", "Lands near 1.2-1.4 billion units a year", "States it is unit shipments not dollar revenue"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Let me build this from the installed base and a replacement cycle. World population is about 8 billion. Not everyone owns a smartphone, since young children and the very poor do not, so I will say a bit over half, call it roughly 4.5 billion users globally. The key driver is how often people replace a phone. People upgrade roughly every three to four years on average, so let me use about 3.5 years. If 4.5 billion people each replace once every 3.5 years, annual replacement sales are 4.5 divided by 3.5, which is around 1.3 billion units. On top of that there are first-time buyers in growing markets, but the installed base is also maturing, so I will only add a modest amount, partly offset by lengthening cycles in rich markets. That keeps me in the range of roughly 1.2 to 1.4 billion phones a year, so I will say about 1.3 billion units. Note this is unit shipments, not dollar revenue. At a blended price of a few hundred dollars the market would be several hundred billion dollars.$x$),
(1874, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Windows In NYC$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$How many windows are there in New York City? Talk me through your reasoning.$x$, $x$["Population of NYC anchored near 8-8.5 million", "Splits stock into residential and commercial", "Windows per dwelling and households estimated", "People per household assumption stated", "Adds offices, retail, schools, hotels as a smaller add-on", "Arrives at an order of magnitude, tens of millions", "Sanity-checks the final number and states the range"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I will anchor on people and buildings. New York City has roughly 8.5 million residents. Assume about 2.5 people per household, so call it 3.4 million households, which I will round to about 3.5 million dwelling units. A typical apartment might have around six windows on average, mixing small studios with larger units. That gives me 3.5 million times 6, so roughly 21 million residential windows. Now commercial and institutional space, meaning offices, retail, schools and hotels. Office towers are very glassy, so even though there are far fewer commercial buildings, I will add a meaningful chunk. Say commercial and institutional windows are roughly half the residential figure, about 10 million. Adding those gives me in the neighborhood of 30 million windows. Given my rounding I would express this as an order of magnitude of tens of millions, call it about 30 million. If I assumed more glass-heavy towers I could push toward 50 million, but tens of millions is the defensible answer.$x$),
(1875, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Ping-Pong Balls Room$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$How many ping-pong balls would it take to completely fill this conference room? Walk me through it.$x$, $x$["Room dimensions estimated, gives volume in cubic meters", "Ball diameter ~4cm, sphere volume per ball computed", "Converts units consistently", "Applies a random-packing efficiency factor near 65-70%", "Effective filled volume divided by ball volume", "Result order of magnitude in the millions, roughly 4-5 million", "States packing inefficiency leaves gaps that reduce the count"]$x$::jsonb, $x$First the room volume. Say this room is about 10 meters long, 8 wide and 3 high, so volume is 10 times 8 times 3, which is 240 cubic meters. A ping-pong ball is about 4 centimeters across, so its radius is 2 centimeters, or 0.02 meters. Its volume is four-thirds pi r cubed, which is about 3.4 times 10 to the minus 5 cubic meters. Spheres do not pack perfectly. Random packing fills roughly two-thirds of the space, so I will apply a 0.65 packing factor. Effective filled volume is 240 times 0.65, about 156 cubic meters. Dividing by the ball volume, 156 divided by 3.4 times 10 to the minus 5, gives roughly 4.6 million. So my estimate is on the order of 4 to 5 million ping-pong balls. A quick sanity check using a 4-centimeter bounding cube per ball gives 240 over 6.4 times 10 to the minus 5, about 3.75 million, which brackets the same few-million order of magnitude.$x$),
(1876, NULL, 'primary', $x$Brainteaser$x$, $x$Data-Center Power Demand$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$Estimate the annual electricity consumption of US data centers, and express it as a share of total US power generation. This is topical given the AI build-out.$x$, $x$["Estimates count or aggregate capacity of US data centers", "Average power draw or load factor per facility assumed", "Builds annual TWh via gigawatts times ~8,760 hours", "US total generation anchored near 4,000-4,300 TWh", "Computes share, lands roughly mid-single-digit toward ~7-8%", "Notes AI and hyperscale as the growth driver and flags uncertainty", "Sanity-checks order of magnitude"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I will go through aggregate capacity, then hours, then compare to total US generation. There are several thousand US data centers, but power is dominated by large hyperscale sites. Let me estimate total IT-plus-cooling power draw at roughly 30 to 40 gigawatts of average load across the fleet, since a single big AI campus can be hundreds of megawatts. Take 35 gigawatts average. There are about 8,760 hours in a year, so annual energy is 35 times 8,760, which is roughly 300,000 gigawatt-hours, or about 300 terawatt-hours. Now the denominator. The US generates on the order of 4,000 to 4,300 terawatt-hours a year. So data centers are about 300 over 4,100, which is roughly 7 to 8 percent. That brackets the public estimates, which put it in the mid-single digits today and rising fast toward roughly 10 percent or more this decade as AI training and inference scale. So my answer is on the order of 300 terawatt-hours, around 7 to 8 percent of US generation, with real uncertainty in that figure.$x$) on conflict do nothing;
